as a close appreciation of recordings made by key rural musicians, black and white, in the 1920s and '30s.The guitar in its many forms has cheered humanity through centuries of upheaval, and The Guitar and the New World offers a new account of this old friend, as well as a transformative look at a hidden chapter of American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBlues musicians -- United States. 0aBlues musicianszUnited States. 0aGuitar makers -- United States. 0aGuitar makerszUnited States. 0aItalian Americans. 0aMusic -- Social aspects -- United States -- History. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPan-American Exposition -- (1901 : -- Buffalo, N.Y.). 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Italian American Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Music. 4aHistory : American History. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845503740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438455037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438455037/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles